# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2016-winter-youth-olympics
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1895-world-allround-speed-skating-championships] The **1895 World Allround Speed Skating Championships** took place at 23 and 24 February 1895 at the ice rink Mjøsen in Hamar, Norway.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1895-world-allround-speed-skating-championships] In 1894 no champion was declared because none of the skaters won three distances.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1895-world-allround-speed-skating-championships] Jaap Eden became the first skater to win two world titles.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1895-world-allround-speed-skating-championships] One could earn the world title only by winning at least three of the four distances, otherwise the title would be vacant.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1895-world-allround-speed-skating-championships] The winner of the 500 and 1500 meter was decided by a skate off of the best four skaters of the distance.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1895-world-allround-speed-skating-championships] Silver and bronze medals were not awarded.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The **1896 Summer Olympics**, officially known as the **Games of the I Olympiad**, and commonly known as **Athens 1896** (Greek: Αθήνα 1896), were the first international Olympic Games held in modern history.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Organised by the International Olympic Committee (IOC), which had been created by French aristocrat Pierre de Coubertin, the event was held in Athens, Greece, from 6 to 15 April 1896.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Fourteen nations (according to the IOC, though the number is subject to interpretation) and 241 athletes (all males; this number is also disputed) took part in the games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Participants were all European or living in Europe, with the exception of the United States team, and over 65% of the competing athletes were Greek.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Winners were given a silver medal, while runners-up received a copper medal.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Retroactively, the IOC has designated the top three finishers in each event as gold, silver, and bronze medalists.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the 14 participating nations earned medals.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On April 6, 1896, American James Connolly became the first Olympic medalist in more than 1,500 years, competing in the triple jump.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals, 11, while host nation Greece won the most medals overall, 47.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The highlight for the Greeks was the marathon victory by their compatriot Spyridon Louis.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The most successful competitor was German wrestler and gymnast Carl Schuhmann, who won four events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Athens had been chosen to stage the inaugural modern Games during a congress organised by Coubertin in Paris on 23 June 1894, during which the IOC was also created.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The main venue was the Panathenaic Stadium, where athletics and wrestling took place; other venues included the Neo Phaliron Velodrome for cycling and the Zappeion for fencing.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The opening ceremony was held in the Panathenaic Stadium on 6 April, during which most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After a speech by the president of the organising committee, Crown Prince Constantine, his father officially opened the Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras and written by Kostis Palamas.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Olympics were regarded as a great success.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Games had the largest international participation of any sporting event to that date.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium overflowed with the largest crowd ever to watch a sporting event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After the Games, Coubertin and the IOC were petitioned by several prominent figures, including Greece's King George and some of the American competitors in Athens, to hold all the following Games in Athens.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] However, the 1900 Summer Olympics were already planned for Paris, and, with the exception of the Intercalated Games of 1906, the Olympics did not return to Greece until the 2004 Summer Olympics, 108 years later.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During the 19th century, several small-scale sports festivals across Europe were named after the ancient Olympic Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1870 Olympics at the Panathenaic stadium, which had been refurbished for the occasion, had an audience of 30,000 people.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Pierre de Coubertin, a French pedagogue and historian, adopted William Penny Brookes's idea to establish a multi-national and multi-sport event (even though the ancient games only allowed male athletes of Greek origin to participate).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In 1890, Coubertin wrote an article in *La Revue Athlétique*, which espoused the importance of Much Wenlock, a rural market town in the English county of Shropshire.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] It was here that, in October 1850, the local physician William Penny Brookes founded the Wenlock Olympian Games, a festival of sports and recreations that included athletics and team sports like cricket, football and quoits.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin also took inspiration from earlier Greek games organised under the name of Olympics by businessman and philanthropist Evangelis Zappas in 1859, 1870 and 1875.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Athens Games were funded by the legacies of Zappas and his cousin Konstantinos Zappas and by George Averoff who had been requested by the Greek government to sponsor the second refurbishment of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek government did this despite the cost of refurbishing the stadium in marble already being funded in full by Evangelis Zappas forty years earlier.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On 18 June 1894, Coubertin organised a congress at the Sorbonne, Paris, to present his plans to representatives of sports societies from 11 countries.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Following his proposal's acceptance by the congress, a date for the first modern Olympic Games was discussed; Coubertin suggested that the Games be held concurrently with the 1900 Universal Exposition of Paris.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Concerned that a six-year waiting period might lessen public interest, congress members opted to hold the inaugural Games in 1896.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] With a date established, members of the congress discussed the selection of a host city.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] It is unknown how Athens was chosen: Coubertin and Demetrius Vikelas's descriptions of the selection process contradicted the congress's official minutes.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Most accounts state that several congressmen first proposed London, but Coubertin dissented.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] After a brief discussion with Vikelas, who represented Greece, Coubertin suggested Athens.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas made the Athens proposal official on 23 June; since Greece had been the original home of the Olympics, the congress unanimously approved the decision.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Vikelas was then elected the first president of the newly established International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The return of the Olympic Games to Greece was well-received by the Greek public, media, and royal family.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Crown Prince conferred their patronage to the games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] However, the country had financial troubles and was in political turmoil.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The country's prime minister frequently alternated between Charilaos Trikoupis and Theodoros Deligiannis during the last years of the 19th century.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] This instability caused Trikoupis and Stephanos Dragoumis, the president of the Zappas Olympic Committee, which had attempted to organise a series of national Olympiads, to believe that Greece could not host the event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In late 1894, the organising committee under Stephanos Skouloudis presented a report that the cost of the Games would be three times higher than originally estimated by Coubertin.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] They concluded the Games could not be held and offered their resignation.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] With the prospect of reviving the Olympic games in doubt, Coubertin and Vikelas commenced a campaign to increase the Olympic movement's popularity.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On 7 January 1895 Vikelas announced that crown prince Constantine would assume the presidency of the organising committee.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] His first responsibility was to raise the funds necessary to host the Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] He relied on the patriotism of the Greek people to motivate them to provide the required finances.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Constantine's enthusiasm increased contributions from the Greek public, raising 330,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,106,157,688 in 2025).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A special set of postage stamps was commissioned; the sale of which raised 400,000 drachmas (equivalent to $1,340,797,197 in 2025).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] At the request of Constantine, businessman George Averoff agreed to pay for the restoration of the Panathenaic Stadium.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] As a tribute to his generosity, a statue of Averoff was constructed and unveiled on 5 April 1896 outside the stadium.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC's first regulation, voted on in 1894, was to allow only amateur athletes to participate in the Olympic Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The various contests were thus held under amateur regulations, except for fencing matches.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The rules and regulations were not uniform, so the Organising Committee chose among the codes of the various national athletic associations.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The jury, the referees and the game director bore the same names as in antiquity (*Ephor*, *Helanodic* and *Alitarc*).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George acted as final referee; according to Coubertin, "his presence gave weight and authority to the decisions of the ephors".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Women could not compete at the 1896 Summer Olympics because Coubertin felt that their inclusion would be "impractical, uninteresting, unaesthetic and incorrect".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Seven venues were used for the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Panathenaic Stadium was the main venue, hosting four of the nine sports contested.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The town of Marathon hosted the marathon event and the individual road race events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Fencing was held at the Zappeion, sport shooting at Kallithea, and tennis at the Athens Lawn Tennis Club.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Swimming was held in the Bay of Zea; it was selected because the organizers of the Games wanted to avoid spending money on constructing a special-purpose swimming venue.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Four of the 1896 venues were reused as competition venues for the 2004 Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The velodrome would be renovated into a football stadium in the 1960s and was known as Karaiskakis Stadium.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] This venue was renovated in 2003 for use as a football venue for the 2004 Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During the 2004 Games, Panathinaiko Stadium hosted the archery competitions and was the finish line for the athletic marathon event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The city of Marathon itself served as the starting point for both marathon events during the 2004 Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Zappeion served as the first home of the organizing committee (ATHOC) for the 2004 Games from 1998 to 1999, and served as the press center for non-accredited media during those Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On Easter Monday 6 April (25 March according to the Julian calendar used in Greece until 1923) the games of the First Olympiad were officially opened.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Panathenaic Stadium was filled with between 16,000 and 80,000 spectators, including King George I of Greece, his wife Olga, and other members of the royal family.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Most of the competing athletes were aligned on the infield, grouped by nation.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, nine bands and 150 choir singers performed an Olympic Hymn, composed by Spyridon Samaras, with words by poet Kostis Palamas.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first announcements regarding the sporting events to be held featured sports like equestrian and cricket, but these plans were not finalised, and these sports did not make the final program for the Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Football is sometimes listed as having been an exhibition or demonstration sport, although whether a football match actually occurred is disputed.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing and sailing events were cancelled on the planned days of competition: sailing due to a lack of special boats in Greece and no foreign entries, and rowing due to poor weather.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 1896 Summer Olympics programme featured 9 sports encompassing 10 disciplines and 43 events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The number of events in each discipline is noted in parentheses.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The athletics events had the most international field of any of the sports.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The major highlight was the marathon, held for the first time in international competition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis, a previously unrecognised water carrier, won the event to become the only Greek athletics champion and a national hero.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Although Greece had been favoured to win the discus and the shot put, the best Greek athletes finished second to American Robert Garrett in both events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] No world records were set, as few top international competitors had elected to compete and the curves of the track were very tight, making fast times in the running events virtually impossible.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Thomas Burke of the United States won the 100-meter race in 12.0 seconds and the 400-meter race in 54.2 seconds.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Burke was the only one who used the "crouch start" (putting his knee on soil), confusing the jury.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Chile claims one athlete, Luis Subercaseaux, who competed for the nation at the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Subercaseaux's results are not listed in the official report, though that report typically includes only winners and Subercaseaux won no medals.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] He was entered to compete in the 100m, 400m and 800m events but is usually listed as a no show.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] An appraisal of a photo of series 2 of the 100 meters sprint, performed by facial recognition experts of the Chilean forensic police, concluded that Subercaseaux was one of the participants.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The day after the official marathon, Stamata Revithi ran the 40-kilometer course in 5 hours 30 minutes, finishing outside Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Some authors, who believe that "Melpomene" and Revithi are the same person, attribute to the latter the more favorable time of 4+1⁄2 hours.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] She was denied entry into the official race as the 1896 Olympics excluded women from competition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The cycling competitions used the rules of the International Cycling Association.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The newly built Neo Phaliron Velodrome hosted the track cycling events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Only one road event was held, a race from Athens to Marathon and back (87 kilometres).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the track events, the best cyclist was Frenchman Paul Masson, who won the one lap time trial, the sprint event, and the 10,000 meters.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the 100 kilometres event, Masson entered as a pacemaker for his compatriot Léon Flameng.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Flameng won the event, after a fall and after stopping to wait for his Greek opponent Georgios Kolettis to fix a mechanical problem.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Austrian fencer Adolf Schmal won the 12-hour race, which was completed by only two cyclists, while the road race event was won by Aristidis Konstantinidis.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The fencing events were held in the Zappeion, which, built with money Evangelis Zappas had given to revive the ancient Olympic Games, had never seen any athletic contests before.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike other sports (in which only amateurs were allowed to take part at the Olympics), professionals were authorised to compete in fencing, though in a separate event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] These masters professionals were considered gentlemen athletes, just like the amateurs.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Four events were scheduled, but the épée event was cancelled for unknown reasons.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The foil event was won by a Frenchman, Eugène-Henri Gravelotte, who beat his countryman, Henri Callot, in the final.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The other two events were won by Greek fencers: Ioannis Georgiadis won the sabre event, and Leonidas Pyrgos won the masters foil, becoming the first Greek Olympic champion in the modern era.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The gymnastics competition was carried out on the infield of the Panathinaiko Stadium.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Germany sent an 11-man team, which won five of the eight events, including both team events: in the team event on the horizontal bar, the German team was the only entry.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Three Germans added individual titles: Hermann Weingärtner won the horizontal bar event, Alfred Flatow won the parallel bars, and Carl Schuhmann, who also won the wrestling event, won the vault.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Louis Zutter, a Swiss gymnast, won the pommel horse, while Greeks Ioannis Mitropoulos and Nikolaos Andriakopoulos were victorious in the rings and rope climbing events, respectively.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A regatta of sailing boats was on the program of the Games of the First Olympiad for 31 March 1896 (Julian calendar).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The event was cancelled: the official English report blamed a lack of specialty boats had not been provided while the German version also cited a lack of foreign competitors.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Rowing races were scheduled for the next day, 1 April 1896 (Julian).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Poor weather caused the event to be postponed to 3 pm and German Berthold Küttner stated that he and Adolf Jäger had lined up for the start of the double sculls, the first event to take place.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The event was further postponed to the next day, but the German team still completed the event in the bad weather: they were presented with the winners medal upon the completion of their row.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The next day, the event was formally cancelled when the weather worsened.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee does not recognize Küttner's recollection of the events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Held at a range at Kallithea, the shooting competition consisted of five events—two using a rifle and three with a pistol.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first event, the military rifle, was won by Pantelis Karasevdas, the only competitor to hit the target with all of his shots.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The second event, for military pistols, was dominated by two American brothers: John and Sumner Paine.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] They became the first siblings to finish first and second in the same event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] To avoid embarrassing their hosts, the brothers decided that John would withdraw from the free pistol event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Sumner Paine won that event, becoming the first relative of an Olympic champion to become Olympic champion himself.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Paine brothers did not compete in the 25-meter pistol event, as the event judges determined that their weapons were not of the required calibre; Ioannis Phrangoudis won the event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The final event, the free rifle, could not be completed due to darkness and was finalised the next morning, with Georgios Orphanidis winning the competition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The swimming competition was held in the open sea because the organizers had refused to spend the money necessary for a specially constructed stadium.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Nearly 20,000 spectators lined the Bay of Zea off the Piraeus coast to watch the events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The water in the bay was cold, and the competitors suffered during their races.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] There were three open events (men's 100-metre freestyle, men's 500-metre freestyle, and men's 1200 metre freestyle), in addition to a special event open only to Greek sailors, all of which were held on the same day (11 April).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] For Alfréd Hajós of Hungary, this meant he could only compete in two of the events, as they were held too close together, which made it impossible for him to adequately recuperate.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Nevertheless, he won the two events in which he swam, the 100 and 1200 meter freestyle.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Hajós later became one of only two Olympians to win a medal in both the athletic and artistic competitions, when he won a silver medal for architecture in 1924.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The 500-meter freestyle was won by Austrian swimmer Paul Neumann, who defeated his opponents by more than a minute and a half.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Although tennis was already a major sport by the end of the 19th century, none of the top players turned up for the tournament in Athens.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The competition was held at the courts of the Athens Lawn Tennis Club, and the infield of the velodrome used for the cycling events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] John Pius Boland, who won the event, had been entered in the competition by a fellow-student of his at Oxford; the Greek, Konstantinos Manos.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] As a member of the Athens Lawn Tennis sub-committee, Manos had been trying, with the assistance of Boland, to recruit competitors for the Athens Games from among the sporting circles of Oxford University.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In the first round, Boland defeated Friedrich Traun, a promising tennis player from Hamburg, who had been eliminated in the 100-meter sprint competition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Boland and Traun decided to team up for the doubles event, in which they reached the final and defeated their Greek opponents after losing the first set.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The sport of weightlifting was still young in 1896, and the rules differed from those in use today.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Competitions were held outdoors, in the infield of the main stadium, and there were no weight limits.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The first event was similar in style to what is now known as the "clean and jerk".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Two competitors stood out: Briton Launceston Elliot and Viggo Jensen of Denmark.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Both of them lifted the same weight, but the jury, with Prince George as the chairman, ruled that Jensen had done so in a better style.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The British delegation, unfamiliar with this tie-breaking rule, lodged a protest.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The lifters were eventually allowed to make further attempts, but neither lifter improved, and Jensen was declared the champion.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Elliot got his revenge in the one hand lift event, which was held immediately after the two-handed one.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Jensen had been slightly injured during his last two-handed attempt and was no match for Elliot, who won the competition easily.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The Greek audience was charmed by the British victor, whom they considered very attractive.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] A curious incident occurred during the weightlifting event: a servant was ordered to remove the weights, which appeared to be a difficult task for him.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Prince George came to his assistance; he picked up the weight and threw it a considerable distance with ease, to the delight of the crowd.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] No weight classes existed for the wrestling competition, held in the Panathenaic Stadium, which meant that there would only be one winner among competitors of all sizes.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The rules used were similar to modern Greco-Roman wrestling, although there was no time limit, and not all leg holds were forbidden (in contrast to current rules).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Apart from the two Greek contestants, all the competitors had previously been active in other sports.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Weightlifting champion Launceston Elliot faced gymnastics champion Carl Schuhmann.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The latter won and advanced into the final, where he met Georgios Tsitas, who had previously defeated Stephanos Christopoulos.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Darkness forced the final match to be suspended after 40 minutes; it was continued the following day, when Schuhmann needed only fifteen minutes to finish the bout.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] On the morning of Sunday 12 April (or 31 March, according to the Julian calendar then used in Greece), King George organised a banquet for officials and athletes (even though some competitions had not yet been held).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] During his speech, he made clear that, as far as he was concerned, the Olympics should be held in Athens permanently.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The official closing ceremony was held the following Wednesday after being postponed from Tuesday due to rain.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Again, the royal family attended the ceremony, which was opened by the national anthem of Greece and an ode composed in ancient Greek by George S.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Robertson, a British athlete and scholar.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Afterwards, the king awarded prizes to the winners.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Unlike today, the first-place winners received a silver medal, an olive branch and a diploma, while runners-up received a copper medal, a laurel branch and a diploma.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Third place winners did not receive a prize.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Some winners also received additional prizes.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Spyridon Louis received a cup from Michel Bréal, a friend of Coubertin, who had conceived the marathon event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Louis then led the medalists on a lap of honour around the stadium, while the Olympic Hymn was played again.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The King then formally announced that the first Olympiad was at an end and left the Stadium, while the band played the Greek national hymn and the crowd cheered.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Like the Greek king, many others supported the idea of holding the next Games in Athens; most of the American competitors signed a letter to the Crown Prince expressing this wish.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Coubertin, however, was heavily opposed to this idea, as he envisioned international rotation as one of the cornerstones of the modern Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] According to his wish, the next Games were held in Paris, although they would be somewhat overshadowed by the concurrent Universal Exposition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The concept of national teams was not a major part of the Olympic movement until the Intercalated Games 10 years later, though many sources list the nationality of competitors in 1896 and give medal counts.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] There are significant conflicts with regard to which nations competed.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee gives a figure of 14, but does not list them.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Different sources provide differing lists of nations; some exclude countries like Chile and Bulgaria, but the IOC lists competitors from both countries.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Egypt is also sometimes included due to the participation of Dimitrios Kasdaglis; however, the IOC classifies him as a Greek athlete.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Belgium and Russia had entered the names of competitors, but no athletes from these countries competed.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] National Olympic Committees did not yet exist.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] Ten of the fourteen participating nations earned medals, in addition to two medals won by mixed teams (teams made up of athletes from multiple nations).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The IOC has retroactively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to the three best placed athletes in each event to comport with more recent traditions.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] In this regard, five of the bronze medalists at the Games are unknown: two in swimming and three in gymnastics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1896-summer-olympics] The United States won the most gold medals (11), while host nation Greece won the most medals overall (47), as well as the most silver (18) and bronze (19) medals, finishing with one fewer gold medal than the United States.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The **1900 Summer Olympics** (French: *Jeux olympiques d'été de 1900*), today officially known as the **Games of the II Olympiad** (*Jeux de la IIe olympiade*) and also known as **Paris 1900**, were an international multi-sport event that took place in Paris, France, from 14 May to 28 October 1900.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No opening or closing ceremonies were held.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the Olympic Congress of 1894, which convened in the Sorbonne building, Pierre de Coubertin proposed that the Olympic Games should take place in Paris in 1900.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, the delegates to the conference were unwilling to wait six years and lobbied to hold the first games in 1896.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A decision was made to hold the first Olympic Games in 1896 in Athens and have Paris host the second Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle (World's Fair).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In total, 1,226 competitors took part in 19 different sports.[note1] This number relies on certain assumptions about which events were and were not "Olympic".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Many athletes, some of whom had won events, were unaware they had competed in the Olympic Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Women took part in the games for the first time, with sailor Hélène de Pourtalès, born Helen Barbey in New York City, becoming the first female Olympic champion.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The decision to hold competitions on a Sunday brought protests from many American athletes, who traveled as representatives of their colleges and were expected to withdraw rather than compete on their religious day of rest.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of the winners in 1900 did not receive medals but were given cups or trophies.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Professionals competed in fencing, as was tradition, and Albert Robert Ayat (France), who won the épée for amateurs and masters, was awarded a prize of 3,000 F (equivalent to €13,896 in 2025).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Some events were contested for the only time in the history of the Games, including angling, motor racing, ballooning, cricket, croquet, Basque pelota, 200m swimming obstacle race and underwater swimming.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympic Games in history to use live animals (pigeons) as targets during the shooting event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The host nation of France fielded 72% of all athletes (720 of the 997) and won the most gold, silver and bronze medal placings.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] U.S. athletes won the second-most in each while fielding the fifth-most participants, 75.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British athletes won the third-most in each while fielding the second most participants, 102.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were held as part of the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Baron de Coubertin believed this would help public awareness of the Olympics and submitted elaborate plans to rebuild the ancient site of Olympia, complete with statues, temples, stadia, and gymnasia.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The director of the Exposition Universelle, Alfred Picard, thought holding an ancient sport event at the Exposition Universelle was an "absurd anachronism".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After thanking de Coubertin for his plans, Picard filed them away and nothing more came of it.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A committee was formed for the organization of the Games, consisting of some of the more able sports administrators of the day, and a provisional program was drawn up.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Sports to be included at the games were track and field athletics, swimming, wrestling, gymnastics, fencing, French and British boxing, river and ocean yacht racing, cycling, golf, lifesaving, archery, weightlifting, rowing, diving, and water polo.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] British and Irish sports associations and several influential American universities and sports clubs announced their desire to compete.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitors from Russia and Australia also confirmed their intentions to travel to Paris.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On 9 November 1898, the Union des Sociétés Françaises de Sports Athlétiques ("Union of the French Societies for Athletic Sports" or USFSA) announced that it would have the sole right to any organized sport held during the World's Fair.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] It was an empty threat, but Viscount Charles de La Rochefoucauld, the nominated head of the organizing committee, stepped down rather than be embroiled in the political battle.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC ceded control of the Games to a new committee to oversee every sporting activity connected to the 1900 Exposition Universelle.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alfred Picard appointed Daniel Mérillon, the head of the French Shooting Association, as president of this organization in February 1899.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mérillon published an entirely different schedule of events, which resulted in many of those who had made plans to compete with the original program withdrawing and refusing to deal with the new committee.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Between May and October 1900, the new organizing committee held many sporting activities alongside the Paris Exposition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The press reported competitions variously as "International Championships", "International Games", "Paris Championships", "World Championships" and "Grand Prix of the Paris Exposition".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These poorly organized games, along with those of 1904, were termed decades later by several historians "The Farcical Games".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Years later, many competitors were unaware that they had competed in the Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While there is an Official Report of these Games, complete records of results do not exist.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] De Coubertin commented later to friends, "It's a miracle that the Olympic Movement survived that celebration".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Before July 2021, the IOC had never decided which events were "Olympic".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In fact, Pierre de Coubertin had ceded that entire determination to the organizers.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC webpage for the 1900 Summer Olympics affirms a total of 95 medal events.[note1] Weightlifting and wrestling were dropped since the 1896 Summer Olympics, while 12 new sports were added.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Among the sports below, only croquet was not an international competition, being contested by French players only.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 14 venues were used at the 1900 Summer Olympics to host 20 sports.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of Paris with Olympic venues marked.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Map of France with Olympic venues marked.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The standard of competition at the Games was variable.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite a poor-quality track, a strong contingent of top-class American collegiate athletes ensured the track and field competitions were of the highest quality.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The tennis gold medalists were all former Wimbledon champions; swimming and fencing events were of a good standard; and even polo, a minority sport for the social elite, was well represented by some of the best players in the game.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Other sports were noticeably weak in both quality and depth.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only athletics, swimming and fencing had competitors from more than ten nations.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The history of the archery competition at the 1900 Olympics is one of confusion.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC currently lists six events with Olympic status, but a case has been made that as many as eight other events equally deserve to be considered part of official Olympic history.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] About 150 archers competed in the six events that later had official status conferred.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, as many as 5,000 were involved in archery competition in conjunction with the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Belgian Hubert Van Innis took two gold medals and one silver and would add to his tally twenty years later in Antwerp.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The track and field events were held at the home of the Racing Club de France at the Croix-Catelan stadium in Bois de Boulogne.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] No track was laid and races took place on an uneven field of grass littered with trees.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Additional events were held for professionals and a series of handicap races also took place.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are not considered official Olympic events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the seven events contested over 400 metres or less, the United States took 13 out of a possible 21 medals.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Athletes from Columbia University, Princeton University and the University of Pennsylvania all won gold medals.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Indeed, two would-be dentists from the University of Pennsylvania were among the stars of the Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Alvin Kraenzlein won 4 individual gold medals, a feat that has never repeated, while Walter Tewksbury took five medals including two golds.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The hurdles in the 400 m hurdle race were 30-foot (9.1 m)-long telegraph poles arranged on the track and the race, uniquely in Olympic competition, had a water jump on the final straight.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Adolphe Klingelhoeffer, who had Brazilian citizenship in 1900, competed for France in three events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] United States dominance in sprinting was matched in the longer track races by United Kingdom.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only George Orton, who won Canada's first Olympic title in the shorter of the two steeplechases, ruined a perfect record for the British.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton won his title less than an hour after placing third in the 400-metre hurdles.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The most contentious of all the events in these Games began and ended in the Bois de Boulogne.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Intended to follow the track of the old city wall, the course was poorly marked out and runners often got lost and had to double back on themselves before continuing.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On some parts of the course, runners had to contend with distractions from cars, bicycles, pedestrians and animals.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Arthur Newton of the United States finished fifth but stated he had not been passed by any other runner during the race.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Another American, Richard Grant, claimed he was run down by a cyclist as he made ground on the leaders.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French honour seemed to have been satisfied when Michel Théato crossed the finish line and a military band struck up La Marseillaise.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However, modern research has revealed that Théato was born in Luxembourg and maintained Luxembourgian citizenship throughout his life.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Hungarian discus thrower Rudolf Bauer was the only non-American crowned as Olympic Champion.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] American domination was even greater in the field events than the track events, with outstanding performances coming from Ray Ewry and Irving Baxter.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Ewry started his Olympic career with a sweep of the three standing jumps, while Baxter finished second to Ewry three times and won both the regular high jump and pole vault.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Meyer Prinstein became the first Jewish Olympic gold medalist in the triple jump.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The chistera form of the game was played at this, the sport's only appearance at full Olympic level.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Two pairs entered and the Spanish partnerships of Amezola and Villota became their nations' first Olympic champions.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The mano form of the game and a chistera tournament for professional players were contested unofficially.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the withdrawal of teams from the Netherlands and Belgium, only two teams played in the cricket tournament.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A team made up of players from the Albion Cricket Club and the Standard Athletic Club, two Paris clubs consisting almost exclusively of British expatriates, played a touring team from the southwest of England.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Devon and Somerset Wanderers were no more than a team of competent club cricketers (made up from Blundells School old boys and members of Castle Cary Cricket Club), and only Montagu Toller and Alfred Bowerman were deemed good enough to play at county level for Somerset.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The game was played before a small crowd at the Vélodrome de Vincennes.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An emphatic second innings bowling performance from Toller captured victory for the visitors as time appeared to be running out for them.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] If the French had held out for five more minutes the game would have been a draw.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Knowledge of the game would have been lost but for the forethought of John Symes, a member of the victorious team, who kept a scorecard in his own writing.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The croquet tournament was notable as it marked the first appearance of women at Olympic level.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Madame Desprès, Madame Filleul-Brohy and Mademoiselle Ohier were eliminated in the first round of competition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A single paying spectator attended the tournament, an elderly English gentleman who travelled from Nice for the early stages.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An unofficial two-ball handicap competition was also held.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This was also the only Olympiad where croquet was part of the official programme, though there was the variant called roque at the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The home nation won six of the nine medals available, including one that was initially awarded to Great Britain until this was reversed in 2024.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of unofficial events were held for both amateurs and professionals.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Equestrian sport made its debut at the Olympic Games with three jumping events being held, plus two other events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Italian rider Gian Giorgio Trissino won a gold and a silver.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He narrowly missed making Olympic history by winning two medals in the same event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competing with two different horses in the high jump, he jointly won the gold medal and finished in 4th place on his second horse.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nineteen nations were represented in the fencing competition, which was held in a field near the cutlery exhibit at the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] French fencers dominated the proceedings but both Cuba and Italy also took titles.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The early rounds of the foil competitions were judged on style rather than the actual result of the contest.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] This meant that some fencers were eliminated without losing a contest while others were defeated and still progressed to the next rounds.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The first football champions at the Olympics were the London amateurs of Upton Park F.C.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A crowd of around 500 spectators saw them defeat their French rivals.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Margaret Ives Abbott, a student of art from Chicago, played in and won a nine-hole golf tournament on an October Tuesday in Paris.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] She died in 1955 without being aware that the tournament was part of the Olympic Games and she had become America's first ever female Olympic champion.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] 135 gymnasts took part in a competition that involved elements from track and field and weightlifting as well as gymnastic disciplines.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Eight separate tournaments were held in 1900 as part of the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Only the Grand Prix Internationale de l'Exposition is counted as an official medal event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Entries were from clubs rather than countries, and the winning Foxhunters club comprised English, Irish and American players.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Mexico won its first medal in this sport, a bronze won by Guillermo Hayden Wright, Marquez de Villavieja and three brothers: Eustaquio de Escandón y Barron, Pablo de Escandón y Barron and Manuel de Escandón y Barron.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Competitions were held on the River Seine.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Following this, officials decided to run another final for the boycotting crews.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Both events are considered official Olympic competitions.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In a number of events, crews saw the advantage of having ultra-lightweight coxswains and recruited local boys for race days.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Most of these remain a mystery; some could have been under ten years old.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Three teams competed in the Rugby tournament.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A French representative team defeated a team from the German city of Frankfurt and Moseley Wanderers from England.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Moseley team had played a full game of rugby in England the day before they made the journey to Paris.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They arrived in the morning, played the match in the afternoon and were back in their home country by the next morning.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The proposed game between the British and German sides was cancelled, and both are credited as silver medalists.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The Franco-Haitian centre Constantin Henriquez become the first black gold medalist.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 sailing regatta differs from every other Olympic regatta in a number of ways.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In most classes, there were two distinct "finals", boats were assigned time handicaps according to their weight within each class and cash prizes were handed out to the winner of each race.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC initially recognized the winner of the first race in each class as Olympic champion except in the case of the 10-20 ton class, which was decided on aggregate time over three races.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] However currently the participants of both first and second races in 3 classes (0-0.5t, 1-2t and 2-3t) are present in the as medalists, so the second races in these 3 classes were recognized by the IOC, as recommended by Olympic historian Bill Mallon.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] To support the recognition of a total of 95 medal events per Mallon's suggestion, one more race in each of 2 other classes (0.5-1t and 3-10t) has been recognized by the IOC.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Thus, for five of the eight events, two gold, two silver and two bronze medals were retrospectively awarded.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Races were held at both Meulan and Le Havre and medals shared among five nations.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] France and Great Britain were the most successful of the countries involved.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A number of people named as members of medal-winning crews by the IOC have been proved not to have competed; others have their participation seriously questioned by historical research.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Switzerland's Konrad Stäheli was the outstanding marksman of the Games, taking a trio of titles and leading his country to the top of the shooting medal table.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The medals were shared between six different nations.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] There is a debate as to whether the live pigeon shooting event was a full Olympic event, Belgian Leon Lunden shot twenty-one birds on his way to the championship.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Up to thirty unofficial shooting events were also held, most involving professional marksmen.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Research has shown that one of the medal events in the IOC database (25m rapid fire pistol, also called military pistol cat.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The muddied waters of the Seine hosted the swimming events in 1900.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Run with the current, the races produced very fast times by the standards of the day.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] John Arthur Jarvis of Great Britain, Frederick Lane of Australia and the German Ernst Hoppenberg each won two titles.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Lane received a 50-pound bronze statue of a horse as a prize.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The obstacle race required both swimming underneath and climbing over rows of boats while Charles de Venville stayed submerged for over a minute to win the underwater swimming event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A high-quality men's tournament saw three past or future Wimbledon champions reach the semi-finals.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Laurence Doherty reached the final when older brother Reggie stepped aside and let his sibling advance to the final.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The two refused to play each other in what they considered a minor tournament.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] On the 11th of July a landmark was reached in the history of the Olympic Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Charlotte Cooper, already three times Wimbledon champion, took the singles championship to become the first individual female Olympic champion, also winning the mixed doubles event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] A combined Sweden/Denmark team, made up of three competitors from each country, defeated the French team to win the title.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of the members of the French team was a Colombian citizen.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] They were left as the only participating teams; the United States had entered but were forced to scratch as three of their team were involved in the final of the hammer.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Edgar Aabye was a journalist covering the Games for the Danish newspaper Politiken and was asked to join the team when another puller was taken ill.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Osborne Swimming Club, representing Great Britain, were unchallenged in the tournament, scoring 29 goals and conceding only 3 in their 3 matches.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the final, they limited the number of shots on goal to avoid humiliating their opponents.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] One of its team members, Victor Lindberg, was from New Zealand, while Thomas William Burgess of the bronze medal-winning Libellule de Paris team represented Great Britain in the swimming events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Games were not governed by a specific Olympic organizing committee, but were instead held as an appendage to the 1900 World's Fair.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] An enormous number of events was held, though many fall short of the standards later required for Olympic championship status.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] After the several initial editions of the Olympic Games, decisions as to which Olympic events were termed "official" and which had "unofficial" or "demonstration" status were usually left to the Olympic organizing committees and/or the IOC.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In the early Olympic Games, however, no decision as to the official status of any event was made at the time of the Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] While a document from 1912 exists, listing results from the 1900 Games, and formed the original basis of the results of the Paris games in the IOC database, the reliability and authenticity of this paper has been questioned by Olympic historians.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further complicating matters, the IOC has never determined which events were Olympic and which were not.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Of the three events that satisfied three criteria, only croquet has been accorded Olympic status.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In this regard, one of the ten croquet players, Marcel Haëntjens, had been believed to be Belgian, and the croquet events were thus considered as international.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Despite the Flemish name, it was discovered in recent times that Haëntjens was French.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Scholastic and military events were also held across a range of sports.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Four planned competitions were not organized due to a lack of participants: balle au tamis, field hockey, jeu de paume and lacrosse.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] According to the International Olympic Committee, 26 nations sent competitors to this edition.[note1] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] When counting the number of participating countries in the early Olympic Games, the IOC does not take into account otherwise unrepresented countries whose citizens competed for other countries.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Modern research shows that at the 1900 Olympics, the athletes of at least four otherwise unrepresented countries competed for other countries in both individual and team sports.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] George Orton, gold medalist in 2500 metres steeplechase event and bronze medalist in 400 metres hurdles event, and Ronald J.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] MacDonald, both of Canada, competed for the U.S. athletics team.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Orton ran for the University of Pennsylvania and was therefore assumed to be American, but he always considered himself a Canadian.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Michel Théato, the winner of the marathon, competed for the French athletics team.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] He was a Luxembourger; however, this was only discovered decades later.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Francisco Henríquez de Zubiría of Colombia was a silver medal-winner on the French tug of war team.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Victor Lindberg of New Zealand was a gold medal-winner on the British water polo team.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The IOC website lists all of them in the results section under their nationalities, but does not include their countries among the 26 participating countries.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Debuting nations at the games included Argentina, Belgium, Bohemia, Cuba, Haiti, India, Mexico, Netherlands, Norway, Persia, Peru, Romania, Russia and Spain.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Nations that participated in the previous games in Athens 1896 but were absent in Paris 1900 included Bulgaria and Chile.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Austria and Hungary competed as two sovereign countries.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The polity known as Austria-Hungary is mistakenly considered a single sovereign country, while in reality was two sovereign states in real union with a single monarch who was titled both emperor of Austria and king of Hungary.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] At the time, Bohemia was part of Austria, while Australia, Canada and India were all part of the British Empire.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Algeria sent four gymnasts who competed for France, while all of Ireland was considered a part of Great Britain: Irish athletes competed in athletics, polo, sailing and tennis.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Further, a Polish fencer represented Russia, a Croatian fencer represented Austria, and two Slovak athletes competed for Hungary.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The concept of "national teams" chosen by National Olympic Committees did not exist at this point in time.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The 1900 Olympics is unique in being the only Olympic Games to feature rectangular medals, which were designed by Frédérique Vernon.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Gilt silver medals were awarded for 1st place in shooting, lifesaving, automobile racing and gymnastics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] Whilst 2nd place silver medals were awarded in shooting, rowing, yachting, tennis, gymnastics, sabre, fencing, equestrian and athletics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With 3rd place bronze medals being awarded in gymnastics, firefighting and shooting.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] In many sports, however, medals were not awarded.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] With most of the listed prizes were cups and other similar trophies.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee has retrospectively assigned gold, silver and bronze medals to all competitors who earned 1st, 2nd and 3rd-place finishes, respectively, in order to bring early Olympics in line with current awards.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For the first Olympic Games (until Antwerp in 1920), it is difficult to give the exact number of medals awarded to some countries, due to the fact that teams were composed of athletes from different countries.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For Olympic Games before 1908 there is no universally accepted definition of nationality, and medal tables may vary depending on the chosen definition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] For example, Australian Stanley Rowley competed as part of a team selected by the Amateur Athletic Association of England.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1900-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1900 Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The **1904 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the III Olympiad** and also known as **St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis 1904**) were an international multi-sport event held in St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, Missouri, United States, from 1 July to 23 November 1904.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Many events were conducted at what is now known as Francis Field on the campus of Washington University in St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] This was the first time that the Olympic Games were held outside Europe.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Tensions caused by the Russo–Japanese War and difficulties in traveling to St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis resulted in very few top-class athletes from outside the United States and Canada taking part in the 1904 Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Only 69–74 of the 651 athletes who competed came from outside North America, and only between 12 and 15 nations were represented in all.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Some events subsequently combined the U.S. national championship with the Olympic championship.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The current three-medal format of gold, silver and bronze for first, second and third place was introduced at the 1904 Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] After the first two editions of the Olympic Games were awarded to Athens and Paris, the IOC's first open bidding process was held for the 1904 Olympics at the 4th IOC Session in Paris in May 1901.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago civic leaders, including University of Chicago president William Rainey Harper, formed the International Olympian Games Association in February 1901 to plan for hosting the Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Shortly before the session began, another American bid was submitted from St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, which was then preparing to host the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, a World's Fair in 1903.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] At the session, representatives of Chicago offered to put $100,000 (equivalent to $3,870,000 in 2025) toward the games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Unable to compete with this, all other countries withdrew their bids before the IOC voted; cities which had previously expressed interest in the 1904 games included Berlin, Copenhagen, and Stockholm.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC delegates then voted between the choices of Chicago and St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis, with Chicago winning unanimously on May 21.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis was forced to postpone its World's Fair from 1903 to 1904, it began planning athletic events that would compete directly with the Olympics in Chicago.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis and planned to hold its national championships at the World's Fair.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In the meantime, Chicago's plans for a new stadium on the shore of Lake Michigan seating 75,000 met considerable opposition from local leaders, including Aaron Montgomery Ward, putting the centerpiece of Chicago's Olympic bid into question.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] On December 23, 1902, fearing that the dispute would permanently damage the Olympic movement, the IOC asked its members to approve, by a postal vote, the transfer of the Olympic Games to St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] When the votes were tallied, IOC founder Pierre de Coubertin telegraphed the Chicago committee on February 10, 1903, to inform them that the Games had been moved.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing, dumbbells, catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling), and the decathlon made their debuts.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The swimming events were held in a temporary pond near Skinker and Wydown Boulevards, where "lifesaving demonstrations" of unsinkable lifeboats for ocean liners took place.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Chicago runner James Lightbody won the steeplechase and the 800 m and then set a natural world record in the 1500 m.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Harry Hillman won both the 200 m and 400 m hurdles and also the flat 400 m.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Sprinter Archie Hahn was champion in the 60 m, 100 m and 200 m.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In this last race, he set an Olympic record in 21.6, a natural record that stood for 28 years.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In the discus, after American Martin Sheridan had thrown exactly the same distance as his compatriot, Ralph Rose (39.28 m), the judges gave them both an extra throw to decide the winner.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Sheridan won the decider and claimed the gold medal.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Ray Ewry again won all three standing jumps.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The team representing Great Britain was awarded a total of two medals, both won by Irish athletes.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The top non-U.S. athlete was Emil Rausch of Germany, who won three swimming events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Zoltán Halmay of Hungary and Charles Daniels of the United States each won two swimming gold medals.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Galt Football Club from Canada won the gold medal in football.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The organizers of the World's Fair held "Anthropology Days" on August 12 and 13.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Since the 1889 Paris Exposition, human zoos, as a key feature of world's fairs, functioned as demonstrations of anthropological notions of race, progress, and civilization.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These goals were followed also at the 1904 World's Fair.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Fourteen hundred indigenous people from Southeast Asia, the Pacific Islands, East Asia, Africa, the Middle East, South America and North America were displayed in anthropological exhibits that showed them in their natural habitats.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Another 1600 indigenous people displayed their culture in other areas of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition (LPE), including on the fairgrounds and at the Model School, where American Indian boarding schools students demonstrated their successful assimilation.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The sporting event itself took place with the participation of about 100 paid indigenous men.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Contests included "baseball throwing, shot put, running, broad jumping, weight lifting, pole climbing, and tugs-of-war before a crowd of approximately ten thousand".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] No women participated in Anthropology Days, though some, notably the Fort Shaw Indian School girls basketball team, did compete in other athletic events at the LPE.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] According to theorist Susan Brownell, world's fairs – with their inclusion of human zoos – and the Olympics were a logical fit at this time, as they "were both linked to an underlying cultural logic that gave them a natural affinity".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Also, one of the original intentions of Anthropology Days was to create publicity for the official Olympic events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The 1904 Summer Olympic program featured 16 sports encompassing 95 events in 18 disciplines.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In July 2021 the IOC accepted the recommendation of Olympic historian Bill Mallon regarding which sports and events should be considered as Olympic.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Boxing made its Olympic debut at the St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The sport has since featured at every Summer Olympics, except for the 1912 Stockholm Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] While wrestling made a return, it was exclusively the newly debuted catch wrestling (which later became freestyle wrestling) as opposed to Greco-Roman style of the 1896 Summer Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Five nations were represented, with each of the 42 competitors having resided in the United States.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Later editions would have both styles of wrestling in their programs.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Basketball, hurling, American football and Gaelic football were featured as unofficial sports.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] There was a demonstration bout of women's boxing.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Baseball is also noted by the World Baseball Softball Confederation to have appeared at the Games, though it does not appear in the list compiled by Olympic historian Bill Mallon and any results are not known.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake is located further west.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Five sports venues were used for the 1904 Summer Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The venues included Glen Echo Country Club, the first golf course constructed west of the Mississippi River, which had opened in 1901.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Three Olympic sports were hosted at Forest Park, the site of the Louisiana Purchase Exposition which was being held concurrently with the Olympics: the Life Saving Exhibition Lake at Forest Park was used for the diving, swimming, and water polo events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Creve Coeur Lake became the first park of St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The Lake has hosted rowing regattas since 1882 and still hosts them as of 2010.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Francis Olympic Field and Gymnasium are still in use on the Washington University in St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] An ornamental gate commemorating the 1904 Games was constructed outside the stadium immediately after the Exposition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] A swimming pool was added to the gymnasium in 1985.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Forest Park, constructed in 1876, is still in use as of 2021 and attracts over 12 million visitors annually.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Glen Echo Country Club remains in use as a golf course today as of 2021.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Athletes from thirteen nations competed in St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Numbers in parentheses indicate the number of known competitors for each nation.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] Louis in 1904, and European tensions caused by the Russo-Japanese War, only 69–74 athletes from outside North America participated in the Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These are the nations that won medals at the 1904 Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The nationalities of some medalists were disputed, as many American athletes were recent immigrants to the United States who had not yet been granted U.S. citizenship.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] These cases saw medals credited to the United States transferred to other countries or mixed teams.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] In addition, the IOC had counted one gold, one silver, and two bronze medals won by the American fencer Albertson Van Zo Post for Cuba instead of the United States.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] The IOC also had shown Charles Tatham as a Cuban medal-winner for individual fencing events (foil and épée) and American silver medalist in the team foil event, but he was an American.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1904-summer-olympics] All are now credited to the United States.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The **1906 Intercalated Games** or **1906 Olympic Games** (Greek: Μεσολυμπιάδα, romanized: *Mesolympiada*, lit.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 'Mesolympics'), held from 22 April 1906 to 2 May 1906, was an international multi-sport event that was celebrated in Athens, Greece.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It was at the time considered to be part of the series of the Olympic Games, and was referred to as the "Second International Olympic Games in Athens" by the International Olympic Committee (IOC).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its influence on the Olympic tradition and the records broken during these Games are recorded in history, but are no longer considered part of the Olympic records.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 894 athletes from 20 nations competed in this competition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The idea behind the Intercalated Games was to have an Olympics in Greece every four years, but this would be the first and last.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The idea was not pursued further, and is sometimes termed the "forgotten Games" in the context of the Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The next Olympic Games was the 1908 Summer Olympics in London; the next time the Olympic Games returned to Greece was 98 years later in 2004, also in Athens.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Intercalated Olympic Games were to be a series of *International Olympic Games* halfway between what is now known as the Games of the Olympiad, old and new.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This proposed series of Games, intercalated in the Olympic Games cycle, was always to be held in Athens and was to have equal status with the international Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] However, the only such Games was held in 1906.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] One reason for the Games in 1906 was to celebrate the tenth anniversary of the 1896 Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The first Intercalated Games had been scheduled by the International Olympic Committee in 1901 as part of a new schedule, where every four years, in between the internationally organised Games, there would be an Intermediate Games held in Athens.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This was a compromise; after the successful Games of Athens 1896, the Greeks suggested they could organise the Games every four years.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Since they had the accommodation and had proven they could hold well-organised Games, they received substantial public support.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] However, Pierre de Coubertin, the founder of the International Olympic Committee, opposed this, as he had intended for the first Games to be in Paris in 1900.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] After Paris had lost the première Olympics, De Coubertin did not want the Games to be permanently hosted elsewhere.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1900 Games were overshadowed by the Exposition Universelle, whose organising committee disagreed with De Coubertin's ideas to such an extent that he resigned.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The organisation of the 1900 Games was haphazard by today's standards, and although some events, such as archery, drew widespread attention, many others were poorly attended.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Historians' opinions still differ over which events should be considered "Olympic".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Consequently, the IOC supported the Greek idea by granting them a second series of quadrennial Games in between the first series.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] This was a departure from the ancient schedule, but it was expected that, if the ancient Greeks could keep a four-year schedule, the modern Olympic Movement could keep a two-year schedule.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] As 1902 was now too close to be logistically workable, and Greece was experiencing political and economic difficulties, the 2nd Olympic Games in Athens were scheduled for 1906, and the IOC as a whole gave Greece full support for the organisation.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, Missouri were overshadowed by the Louisiana Purchase Exposition, and their organisation was even worse than that of Paris 1900, while travel difficulties meant that only 20% of the athletes were non-American; of these, half were Canadian.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It was clear the Olympic Movement was in a dire situation and desperately needed to recapture the spirit of Athens 1896.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It also needed to do so quickly, as to those who did not participate in St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Louis, 1908 was a gap of eight years, by which time there would be little, if any, goodwill left for the Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] To make matters worse, Rome, the proposed host for 1908, was also planning an exhibition at the same time as the Games, which had been responsible for the failures of Paris and St.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] To the IOC, the 1906 Athens Games being just around the corner would have been a lifeline.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] While De Coubertin still opposed the idea and did not do anything more than his function required of him, the IOC as a whole gave the Greek organising committee full support for the organisation.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These games offered Greece the huge opportunity to show that it was important to Europe's present and its past.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] It is clear from the beginning that the Olympic Games 1906 became "a grand project far beyond the status of a mere sports meeting", with new structures built to accommodate the events including the restoration of the ancient stadium in Athens.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games were quite successful: unlike the Games of 1900, 1904 or 1908, they were not stretched out over several months, and unlike 1900 and 1904, they were not overshadowed by an international exposition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Their crisp implementation was most likely instrumental in the continued existence of the Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These, along with various other changes, are now accepted as tradition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Games were held from 22 April to 2 May 1906, in Athens, Greece.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] They took place in the Panathenaic Stadium, which had already hosted the 1896 Games and the earlier Zappas Olympics of 1870 and 1875.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The Games excluded several disciplines that had occurred during the past two Games; it was unclear whether they ought to have been part of the Olympic Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Added to the program were the javelin throw and the pentathlon.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1906 Games is noted for its opening and closing ceremonies, which initiated this tradition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] The 1908 Games introduced the tradition of the host coming in as the last in the parade also.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These were the first Games to include an opening ceremony with athletes marching into the stadium as national teams behind their flags.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] King George I officially opened the Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] Six thousand schoolchildren took part in the first ever Olympic closing ceremony.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 854 athletes, 848 men and six women, from 20 countries, competed at the 1906 Intercalated Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] 78 events in 14 disciplines, comprising 12 sports, were part of the 1906 Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1906-intercalated-games] These medals were distributed but are no longer recognized by the International Olympic Committee.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The **1908 Summer Olympics** (officially the **Games of the IV Olympiad** and also known as **London 1908**) were an international multi-sport event held in London, England, from 27 April to 31 October 1908.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games were relocated to London after Italy withdrew from hosting on financial grounds.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Archival research has established that the British Olympic Association was already privately exploring the possibility of London hosting the Games as early as 5 January 1906, three months before the eruption began.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] London was formally confirmed as host on 19 November 1906.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Rome eventually hosted the Games in 1960.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These were the fourth chronological modern Summer Olympics in keeping with the now-accepted four-year cycle as opposed to the alternate four-year cycle of the proposed Intercalated Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The IOC president for these Games was Baron Pierre de Coubertin.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Lasting a total of 187 days (six months and four days), these were the longest Games in modern Olympics history.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] There were four bids for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Rome was selected ahead of London, Berlin and Milan.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The selection was made at the 6th IOC Session in London in 1904.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Italian authorities were preparing to stage the games when Mount Vesuvius erupted on 7 April 1906, devastating the city of Naples.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Funds were diverted to the reconstruction of Naples, so a new host country was required.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] During the Intercalated Games of Athens, still in April 1906, Coubertin approached Lord Desborough about alternatively hosting in London.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Accepting the offer and with a mere 18 months in which to prepare, London was selected for the first time to hold the Games, which were held at White City alongside the Franco-British Exhibition, at the time the more noteworthy event.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The White City Stadium, built in short time for the Games, held 68,000 people, with full crowds turning up to watch the events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The stadium track was three laps to the mile (536.448 metres per lap), as the current standard of 400 metres did not exist until 1962, with a pool (for swimming and diving events) and platforms (for wrestling and gymnastics) in the centre field.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] On the opening day, following the practice introduced at the Intercalated Games of 1906, teams paraded behind national flags.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Olympics also prompted establishment of standard rules for sports, and selection of judges from different countries rather than just the host.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] One reason was the 400 metre race, in which a US runner, John Carpenter, was accused by the British officials of interfering with a British runner.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Part of the problem was the different definition of interference under British and international rules (the events were held under British rules by the decision of the Organising Committee).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The officials decided to disqualify Carpenter and ordered a second final race without him.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] British Halswelle was to face the other two finalists.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These athletes, William Robbins and John Taylor, were both Americans and decided not to participate in the repeat of the final to protest against the judges' decision.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Halswelle was thus the only medallist in the 400 metres.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The most famous incident of the games came at the end of the marathon.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Dorando Pietri, Italy, began his race at a rather slow pace, but in the second half of the course began a powerful surge moving him into second position by the 32 km (20 mi) mark, 4 minutes behind South African Charles Hefferon.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] When he knew that Hefferon was in crisis, Pietri further increased his pace, overtaking him at the 39 km (24 mi) mark.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The effort took its toll and with only two kilometres to go, Pietri began to feel the effects of extreme fatigue and dehydration.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] When he entered the stadium, he took the wrong path and when umpires redirected him, he fell down for the first time.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] He got up with their help, in front of 75,000 spectators.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] He fell four more times, and each time the umpires helped him up.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] In the end, though totally exhausted, he managed to finish the race in first place.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Of his total time of 2h 54min 46s, ten minutes were needed for that last 340 metres.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The American team immediately lodged a complaint against the help Pietri received from the umpires.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The complaint was accepted and Pietri was disqualified and removed from the final standings of the race.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Since he had not been responsible for his disqualification, Queen Alexandra awarded him a gilded silver cup the next day.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These Games were the first to include winter events, as had originally been proposed for the Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] There were four figure skating events, although held on 28 and 29 October, months after most of the other events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Oscar Swahn from Sweden, who won the gold medal for running deer shooting, became the oldest Olympic champion of all time, and set another age record by being 72 years and 279 days old during his triumph at the 1920 Summer Olympics in Antwerp, Belgium.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] One of the more unusual shooting events in 1908 was Olympic dueling.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The discipline, which was an associate event (that is, not official), was performed by facing opponents wearing protective clothing and masks and firing wax bullets.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] American John Taylor was a member of the winning medley relay team, making him the first African-American athlete to win an Olympic gold medal.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Times for the winning team were United States (3:29.4): William Hamilton, 200 metres (22.0); Nathaniel Cartmell, 200 metres (22.2); John Taylor, 400 metres (49.8); and Melvin Sheppard, 800 metres (1:55.4).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Less than five months after returning from the Olympic Games in London, Taylor died of typhoid fever on 2 December 1908 at the age of 26.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The budget of the organising committee showed a cost of £15,000; over one-third was labelled "entertainment expense".
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Donations were the major source of revenue; only 28% of income derived from ticket sales.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Total receipts of £21,378 resulted in organisers claiming a profit.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Construction of the White City Stadium, which cost the government about £60,000, was not counted.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Twenty-two sports, representing 110 events in 25 sporting disciplines, were competed.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] A golf tournament had also been planned but it was cancelled a few days before it was scheduled to start.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Swimming, diving, and water polo are considered three disciplines of the same sport, *aquatics*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] At the time, tug-of-war was part of athletics and the two different football codes (association and rugby (union)) were listed together.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The International Olympic Committee now considers tug-of-war a separate sport as well as referring to association football as simply "football" and to rugby union as "rugby." In one of seven cycling events (cycling sprint) no medals were awarded.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The sailing program was open for a total of five sailing classes, but actually only four sailing events were competed.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Cycle polo, glima and pistol dueling were demonstration sports.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Thirteen sports venues were used for the 1908 Summer Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The first winter sports took place at Prince's Skating Club in Knightsbridge.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] White City Stadium served as a precursor to modern stadiums.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The figure skating events were not held at the next Olympics in Stockholm, but returned for the 1920 Games in Antwerp, heralding the first Winter Olympics that took place in Chamonix in 1924.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] White City was the main venue for the 1934 British Empire Games (known as the Commonwealth Games since 1978) and, before its demolition in 1985, also served as a venue for the 1966 FIFA World Cup.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The All England Lawn Tennis Club continues to host the Wimbledon championships and is the only venue of the 1908 Games that was used for the 2012 Summer Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Bisley and Henley served as venues in the 1948 Games when the Olympics returned to London forty years later.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The 1908 Games featured athletes representing 22 National Olympic Committees.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Finland, Turkey and New Zealand (as part of the team from Australasia) made their first appearance at the Olympic Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] The fact that the United Kingdom competed as a single team was upsetting to some Irish competitors, who felt that Ireland should compete on its own, despite being part of the UK at the time.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] They relied on the precedent set by Grand Duchy of Finland, which while being a part of the Russian Empire, competed in London as a separate country.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Fearing an Irish boycott, the authorities changed the name of the team to Great Britain/Ireland, and in two sports, field hockey and polo, Ireland participated as a separate country, winning silver medals in both, although their medals counted towards the UK's tally.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Irish athletes in the United States were not affected by this controversy, and many Irish immigrants to the United States competed for the U.S.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team as members of the Irish American Athletic Club.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Members of the Irish American Athletic Club won ten of the U.S.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Olympic team's total 23 gold medals, or as many as the nations of France, Germany and Italy combined.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] Britain had more than a quarter of competitors in their team, with 676, compared to 112 on the American team which placed second in the medal standings.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/1908-summer-olympics] These are the top ten nations that won medals at the 1908 Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The **2016 Winter Youth Olympics** (Norwegian: *Olympiske vinterleker for ungdom 2016*; Nynorsk: *Olympiske vinterleikane for ungdom 2016*), officially known as the **II Winter Youth Olympic Games**, took place in and around Lillehammer, Norway, from 12 to 21 February 2016.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] They were the fourth Youth Olympic Games and the second winter edition.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Lillehammer was awarded the games on 7 December 2011 as the only candidate.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The games reused venues from the 1994 Winter Olympics; this made Lillehammer the first city to host both regular and Youth Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] In addition to Lillehammer Municipality, Olympic events were staged at venues in Hamar Municipality, Gjøvik Municipality and Øyer Municipality.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Lillehammer was the only city to bid for the games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The Norwegian Olympic Committee talked with Norwegian and regional authorities to investigate a bid and ultimately submitted a bid to the IOC.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Upon the deadline for bidding, they were the only city to bid.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Lillehammer hosted the 1994 Winter Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] They bid for the 2012 Winter Youth Olympics, but failed to become a candidate.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Lake Placid, Lucerne, Zaragoza and Sofia all expressed interest in bidding but ultimately failed to submit any bids.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] On 7 December 2011, the International Olympic Committee selected Lillehammer as the host city of the 2016 Winter Youth Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] In January 2012, Siri Hatlen was appointed as head of the Lillehammer 2016 Organizing Committee.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] At the Closing ceremony of the 2012 Winter Youth Olympics in Innsbruck, Lillehammer was handed the Olympic Flag.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Tomas Holmestad (33) is CEO of Lillehammer 2016, which holds office at Oppland Fylkeskommune.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] In August 2014, Lillehammer Organizing Committee counts 20 employees, and this number were expected to rise to 70-80 employees in January 2016.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Nine competition and eleven non-competition venues were used, with all except the Youth Olympic Village in Lillehammer being existing venues.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The games were held in four municipalities: Lillehammer, Hamar, Gjøvik and Øyer.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The former three are located nearby the lake of Mjøsa and each have about 27,000 residents, while Øyer has 5,000 residents and is located in the valley of Gudbrandsdalen.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] There were five competition venues in Lillehammer, two in Hamar and one in Gjøvik and Øyer.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] In Lillehammer, the twin ski jumping hill of Lysgårdsbakken has a spectator capacity of 35,000.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Lysgårdsbakken has a hill size of 138 and a K-point of 120, while the normal hill has a hill size of 100 and a K-point of 90.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Birkebeineren Ski Stadium hosted cross-country skiing, biathlon and Nordic combined, with the stadium itself having a capacity for 31,000 spectators during cross-country skiing and 13,500 during biathlon.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] In addition, spectators could watch from along the tracks.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Kanthaugen Freestyle Arena has a capacity for 15,000 spectators and hosted freestyle skiing and half-pipe snowboarding.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Lillehammer Olympic Bobsleigh and Luge Track is located at Hunderfossen and is the only bobsleigh, luge and skeleton track in the Nordic Countries.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Kristins Hall hosted both ice hockey and curling.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Gjøvik Olympic Cavern Hall is located in a man-made cave and featured the short track speed skating events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] In Hamar, Vikingskipet hosted long track speed skating and Hamar Olympic Amphitheatre hosted figure skating.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Alpine skiing and slopestyle snowboarding were undertaken at Hafjell in Øyer.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Lysgårdsbakken also hosted the opening ceremony.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The medal ceremonies took place in the town plaza.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Athletes and leader accommodation were provided at two Olympic Villages, one in Lillehammer for the Lillehammer and Øyer-based events, and one in Hamar for the Hamar and Gjøvik-based events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The Lillehammer village consisted of student apartments in combination with a hotel and apartment resort.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] They used Håkons Hall (who also hosted the closing ceremony) for dining.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The Hamar village was Hotel Scandic Hamar.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] In addition, there are five designated cultural venues in Lillehammer: Kulturhuset Banken, Lillehammer Art Museum, Lillehammer University College, Maihaugen and the Nansen Academy.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The Main Media Centre was located at Mesna Upper Secondary School, which is adjacent to Stampesletta.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] All the competition venues were built ahead of the 1994 Winter Olympics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Kristins Hall is the only venue not used during those Games, while Håkons Hall and Kvitfjell were used.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] During Lillehammer 2016 Youth Olympic Games, Håkonshall was the venue for the Learn & Share program, whilst Kristins Hall was the official venue for ice hockey and curling.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Kvitfjell was not used, and Hafjell was the main venue for downhill skiing, snowboard, and freeskiing instead.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Lillehammer organizing committee launched an international mascot design competition in March and April 2014.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The competition required that the design proposals would be on an animal (ordinary animal or a fantasy one), look youthful, be kind and open, sporty, and represent the look of Lillehammer 2016 Winter Youth Olympic Games.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] LYOGOC received over 50 proposals from all over the world, and a jury consisting of Birgit Skarstein, Julie Strømsvåg, Simen Staalnacke, and Marianne Aagotnes, selected three finalists.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The final proposals were presented on the official Facebook page of Lillehammer 2016, where fans could vote on their favorite.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] It was the Lynx that won the competition, designed by 19-year-old Line Ansethmoen.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Also a cultural programme was a part of the event, in which for example bandy was featured.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The Youth Olympic Games featured 7 sports and 15 disciplines.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The 70 events included 5 mixed team events (Mixed-NOCs), 9 mixed team events (NOCs), 29 boy's events, and 27 girl's events.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] A number of events have been added to the programme.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The countries listed below have qualified at least one provisional athlete.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] 7 countries (Colombia, Israel, Jamaica, Kenya, Malaysia, Portugal and Timor Leste) made their Winter Youth Olympic Games debut.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] The top ten listed National Olympic Committees (NOCs) by number of gold medals are listed below with the host nation, Norway, being highlighted.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/2016-winter-youth-olympics] Medals won by teams of athletes from more than one NOC are included in the table as medals awarded to a mixed-NOCs team.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF has its roots in "The Camelot Project" initiated by Adobe co-founder John Warnock in 1991.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF was standardized as ISO 32000 in 2008.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] It is maintained by ISO TC 171 SC 2 WG8, of which the PDF Association is the committee manager.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The last edition as ISO 32000-2:2020 was published in December 2020.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF files may contain a variety of content besides flat text and graphics including logical structuring elements, interactive elements such as annotations and form-fields, layers, rich media (including video content), three-dimensional objects using U3D or PRC, and various other data formats.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The PDF specification also provides for encryption and digital signatures, file attachments, and metadata to enable workflows requiring these features.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The development of PDF began in 1991 when John Warnock wrote a paper for a project then code-named Camelot, in which he proposed the creation of a simplified version of PostScript called Interchange PostScript (IPS).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Unlike traditional PostScript, which was tightly focused on rendering print jobs to output devices, IPS would be optimized for displaying pages to any screen and any platform.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Adobe made the PDF specification available free of charge in 1993.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In the early years PDF was popular mainly in desktop publishing workflows, and competed with several other formats, including DjVu, Envoy, Common Ground Digital Paper, Farallon Replica and even Adobe's own PostScript format.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF was a proprietary format controlled by Adobe until it was released as an open standard on July 1, 2008, and published by the International Organization for Standardization as ISO 32000-1:2008, at which time control of the specification passed to an ISO Committee of volunteer industry experts.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In 2008, Adobe published a Public Patent License to ISO 32000-1 granting royalty-free rights for all patents owned by Adobe necessary to make, use, sell, and distribute PDF-compliant implementations.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] These proprietary technologies are not standardized, and their specification is published only on Adobe's website.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Many of them are not supported by third-party implementations of PDF.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] ISO published version 2.0 of PDF, ISO 32000-2 in 2017, replacing the specification provided by Adobe.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In December 2020, the second edition of PDF 2.0, ISO 32000-2:2020, was published, with clarifications, corrections, and critical updates to normative references ISO 32000-2 does not include any proprietary technologies as normative references.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In April 2023 the PDF Association made ISO 32000-2 available for download free of charge.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] A PDF file is often a combination of vector graphics, text, and bitmap graphics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In later PDF revisions, a PDF document can also support links (inside document or web page), forms, JavaScript (initially available as a plugin for Acrobat 3.0), or any other types of embedded contents that can be handled using plug-ins.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PostScript is a page description language run in an interpreter to generate an image.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] It can handle graphics and has standard features of programming languages such as branching and looping.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF is a subset of PostScript, simplified to remove certain control flow features, while graphics commands remain.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PostScript was not intended for long-term storage and real-time interactive rendering of electronic documents to computer monitors, so there was no need to support anything other than consecutive rendering of pages.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] If there was an error in the final printed output, the user would correct it at the application level and send a new print job in the form of an entirely new PostScript file.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Traditionally, to go from PostScript to PDF, a source PostScript file (that is, an executable program) is used as the basis for generating PostScript-like PDF code (see, e.g., Adobe Distiller).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] This is done by applying standard compiler techniques like loop unrolling, inlining and removing unused branches, resulting in code that is purely declarative and static.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The result is then packaged into a container format, together with all necessary dependencies for correct rendering (external files, graphics, or fonts to which the document refers), and compressed.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF since v1.6 supports embedding of interactive 3D documents: 3D drawings can be embedded using U3D or PRC and various other data formats.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] A PDF file is organized using ASCII characters, except for certain elements that may have binary content.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The file starts with a header containing a magic number (as a readable string) and the version of the format, for example `%PDF-1.7`.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The format is a subset of a COS ("Carousel" Object Structure) format.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Comments using 8-bit characters prefixed with the percent sign (`%`) may be inserted.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Objects may be either *direct* (embedded in another object) or *indirect*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Indirect objects are numbered with an *object number* and a *generation number* and defined between the `obj` and `endobj` keywords if residing in the document root.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Beginning with PDF version 1.5, indirect objects (except other streams) may also be located in special streams known as *object streams* (marked `/Type /ObjStm`).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] This technique enables non-stream objects to have standard stream filters applied to them, reduces the size of files that have large numbers of small indirect objects and is especially useful for *Tagged PDF*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Object streams do not support specifying an object's *generation number* (other than 0).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] An index table, also called the cross-reference table, is located near the end of the file and gives the byte offset of each indirect object from the start of the file.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] This design allows for efficient random access to the objects in the file, and also allows for small changes to be made without rewriting the entire file (*incremental update*).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Before PDF version 1.5, the table would always be in a special ASCII format, be marked with the `xref` keyword, and follow the main body composed of indirect objects.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Version 1.5 introduced optional *cross-reference streams*, which have the form of a standard stream object, possibly with filters applied.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Such a stream may be used instead of the ASCII cross-reference table and contains the offsets and other information in binary format.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The format is flexible in that it allows for integer width specification (using the `/W` array), so that for example, a document not exceeding 64 KiB in size may dedicate only 2 bytes for object offsets.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] To ensure backward compatibility, a hybrid-reference PDF file may include both traditional cross-reference tables and cross-reference streams, allowing older PDF processors to read the file while still taking advantage of the new features introduced in version 1.5.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Within each page, there are one or multiple content streams that describe the text, vector and images being drawn on the page.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The content stream is stack-based, similar to PostScript.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] There are two layouts to the PDF files: non-linearized (not "optimized") and linearized ("optimized").
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Non-linearized PDF files can be smaller than their linear counterparts, though they are slower to access because portions of the data required to assemble pages of the document are scattered throughout the PDF file.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF files may be optimized using Adobe Acrobat software or QPDF.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Page dimensions are not limited by the format itself.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The basic design of how graphics are represented in PDF is very similar to that of PostScript, except for the use of transparency, which was added in PDF 1.4.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF graphics use a device-independent Cartesian coordinate system to describe the surface of a page.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] A PDF page description can use a matrix to scale, rotate, or skew graphical elements.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] A key concept in PDF is that of the *graphics state*, which is a collection of graphical parameters that may be changed, saved, and restored by a *page description*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] As in PostScript, vector graphics in PDF are constructed with *paths*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Paths are usually composed of lines and cubic Bézier curves, but can also be constructed from the outlines of text.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Unlike PostScript, PDF does not allow a single path to mix text outlines with lines and curves.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Paths can be stroked, filled, filled then stroked, or used for clipping.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Strokes and fills can use any color set in the graphics state, including *patterns*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The simplest is the *tiling pattern* in which a piece of artwork is specified to be drawn repeatedly.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] This may be a *colored tiling pattern*, with the colors specified in the pattern object, or an *uncolored tiling pattern*, which defers color specification to the time the pattern is drawn.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Beginning with PDF 1.3 there is also a *shading pattern*, which draws continuously varying colors.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] There are seven types of shading patterns of which the simplest are the *axial shading* (Type 2) and *radial shading* (Type 3).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Raster images in PDF (called *Image XObjects*) are represented by dictionaries with an associated stream.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The dictionary describes the properties of the image, and the stream contains the image data.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] (Less commonly, small raster images may be embedded directly in a page description as an *inline image*.) Images are typically *filtered* for compression purposes.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Normally all image content in a PDF is embedded in the file.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] But PDF allows image data to be stored in external files by the use of *external streams* or *Alternate Images*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Standardized subsets of PDF, including PDF/A and PDF/X, prohibit these features.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Text in PDF is represented by *text elements* in page content streams.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] A text element specifies that *characters* should be drawn at certain positions.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The characters are specified using the *encoding* of a selected *font resource*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] A font object in PDF is a description of a digital typeface.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] It may either describe the characteristics of a typeface, or it may include an embedded *font file*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The latter case is called an *embedded font* while the former is called an *unembedded font*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The font files that may be embedded are based on widely used standard digital font formats: Type 1 (and its compressed variant CFF), TrueType, and (beginning with PDF 1.6) OpenType.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Additionally PDF supports the Type 3 variant in which the components of the font are described by PDF graphic operators.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] These fonts, or suitable substitute fonts with the same metrics, should be available in most PDF readers, but they are not *guaranteed* to be available in the reader, and may only display correctly if the system has them installed.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Fonts may be substituted if they are not embedded in a PDF.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Within text strings, characters are shown using *character codes* (integers) that map to glyphs in the current font using an *encoding*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] There are several predefined encodings, including *WinAnsi*, *MacRoman*, and many encodings for East Asian languages and a font can have its own built-in encoding.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The encoding mechanisms in PDF were designed for Type 1 fonts, and the rules for applying them to TrueType fonts are complex.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] For large fonts or fonts with non-standard glyphs, the special encodings *Identity-H* (for horizontal writing) and *Identity-V* (for vertical) are used.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] With such fonts, it is necessary to provide a *ToUnicode* table if semantic information about the characters is to be preserved.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] A text document which is scanned to PDF without the text being recognised by optical character recognition (OCR) is an image, with no fonts or text properties.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The original imaging model of PDF was *opaque*, similar to PostScript, where each object drawn on the page completely replaced anything previously marked in the same location.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In PDF 1.4 the imaging model was extended to allow transparency.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] When transparency is used, new objects interact with previously marked objects to produce blending effects.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The addition of transparency to PDF was done by means of new extensions that were designed to be ignored in products written to PDF 1.3 and earlier specifications.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] As a result, files that use a small amount of transparency might be viewed acceptably by older viewers, but files making extensive use of transparency could be viewed incorrectly by an older viewer.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The transparency extensions are based on the key concepts of *transparency groups*, *blending modes*, *shape*, and *alpha*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The model is closely aligned with the features of Adobe Illustrator version 9.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The blend modes were based on those used by Adobe Photoshop at the time.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] When the PDF 1.4 specification was published, the formulas for calculating blend modes were kept secret by Adobe.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The concept of a transparency group in PDF specification is independent of existing notions of "group" or "layer" in applications such as Adobe Illustrator.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Those groupings reflect logical relationships among objects that are meaningful when editing those objects, but they are not part of the imaging model.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] A **tagged PDF** (see clause 14.8 in ISO 32000) includes document structure and semantics information to enable reliable text extraction and accessibility.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Technically speaking, tagged PDF is a stylized use of the format that builds on the logical structure framework introduced in PDF 1.3.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Tagged PDF defines a set of standard structure types and attributes that allow page content (text, graphics, and images) to be extracted and reused for other purposes.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Tagged PDF is not required in situations where a PDF file is intended only for print.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Since the feature is optional, and since the rules for tagged PDF were relatively vague in ISO 32000-1, support for tagged PDF among consuming devices, including assistive technology (AT), is uneven as of 2021.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] ISO 32000-2, however, includes an improved discussion of tagged PDF which is anticipated to facilitate further adoption.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] An ISO-standardized subset of PDF specifically targeted at accessibility, PDF/UA, was first published in 2012.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] With the introduction of PDF version 1.5 (2003) came the concept of Layers.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Layers, more formally known as Optional Content Groups (OCGs), refer to sections of content in a PDF document that can be selectively viewed or hidden by document authors or viewers.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] This capability is useful in CAD drawings, layered artwork, maps, multi-language documents, etc.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Basically, it consists of an Optional Content Properties Dictionary added to the document root.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] This dictionary contains an array of Optional Content Groups (OCGs), each describing a set of information and each of which may be individually displayed or suppressed, plus a set of Optional Content Configuration Dictionaries, which give the status (Displayed or Suppressed) of the given OCGs.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] A PDF file may be encrypted, for security, in which case a password is needed to view or edit the contents.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF 2.0 defines 256-bit AES encryption as the standard for PDF 2.0 files.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The PDF Reference also defines ways that third parties can define their own encryption systems for PDF.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF files may be digitally signed, to provide secure authentication; complete details on implementing digital signatures in PDF are provided in ISO 32000-2.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF files may also contain embedded DRM restrictions that provide further controls that limit copying, editing, or printing.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] These restrictions depend on the reader software to obey them, so the security they provide is limited.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The user password encrypts the file, while the owner password does not, instead relying on client software to respect these restrictions.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] An owner password can easily be removed by software, including some free online services.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Thus, the use restrictions that a document author places on a PDF document are not secure, and cannot be assured once the file is distributed; this warning is displayed when applying such restrictions using Adobe Acrobat software to create or edit PDF files.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Even without removing the password, most freeware or open source PDF readers ignore the permission "protections" and allow the user to print or make copies of excerpts of the text as if the document were not limited by password protection.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Beginning with PDF 1.5, Usage rights (UR) signatures are used to enable additional interactive features that are not available by default in a particular PDF viewer application.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The signature is used to validate that the permissions have been granted by a bona fide granting authority.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] For example, Adobe Systems grants permissions to enable additional features in Adobe Reader, using public-key cryptography.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Adobe Reader verifies that the signature uses a certificate from an Adobe-authorized certificate authority.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Any PDF application can use this same mechanism for its own purposes.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Under specific circumstances including non-patched systems of the receiver, the information the receiver of a digital signed document sees can be manipulated by the sender after the document has been signed by the signer.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PAdES (*PDF Advanced Electronic Signatures*) is a set of restrictions and extensions to PDF and ISO 32000-1 making it suitable for advanced electronic signatures.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] This is published by ETSI as TS 102 778.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF files can have file attachments which processors may access and open or save to a local filesystem.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF files can contain two types of metadata.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The first is the Document Information Dictionary, a set of key/value fields such as author, title, subject, creation and update dates.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] This is optional and is referenced from an `Info` key in the trailer of the file.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] A small set of fields is defined and can be extended with additional text values if required.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In PDF 1.4, support was added for Metadata Streams, using the Extensible Metadata Platform (XMP) to add XML standards-based extensible metadata as used in other file formats.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF 2.0 allows metadata to be attached to any object in the document, such as information about embedded illustrations, fonts, and images, as well as the whole document (attaching to the document catalog), using an extensible schema.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF documents can also contain display settings, including the page display layout and zoom level in a Viewer Preferences object.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Adobe Reader uses these settings to override the user's default settings when opening the document.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The free Adobe Reader cannot remove these settings.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF files can be created specifically to be accessible to people with disabilities.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF file formats in use as of 2014 can include tags, text equivalents, captions, audio descriptions, and more.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Some software can automatically produce tagged PDFs, but this feature is not always enabled by default.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Leading screen readers, including JAWS, Window-Eyes, Hal, and Kurzweil 1000 and 3000 can read tagged PDFs.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Moreover, tagged PDFs can be re-flowed and magnified for readers with visual impairments.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Adding tags to older PDFs and those that are generated from scanned documents can present some challenges.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] One of the significant challenges with PDF accessibility is that PDF documents have three distinct views, which, depending on the document's creation, can be inconsistent with each other.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The three views are (i) the physical view, (ii) the tags view, and (iii) the content view.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The physical view is displayed and printed (what most people consider a PDF document).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The tags view is what screen readers and other assistive technologies use to deliver high-quality navigation and reading experience to users with disabilities.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The content view is based on the physical order of objects within the PDF's content stream and may be displayed by software that does not fully support the tags' view, such as the Reflow feature in Adobe's Reader.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF/UA, the International Standard for accessible PDF based on ISO 32000-1 was first published as ISO 14289–1 in 2012 and establishes normative language for accessible PDF technology.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF/UA addresses accessibility of the PDF format it brings the ideas behind WCAG 2.0 to establish PDF-specific accessibility rules.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] AcroForms were introduced in the PDF 1.2 format.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] AcroForms permit the uses of objects (*e.g.* text boxes, Radio buttons, *etc.*) and some code (*e.g.* JavaScript).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Alongside the standard PDF action types, interactive forms (AcroForms) support submitting, resetting, and importing data.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The "submit" action transmits the names and values of selected interactive form fields to a specified uniform resource locator (URL).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] based on PDF, uses the same syntax and has essentially the same file structure, but is much simpler than PDF since the body of an FDF document consists of only one required object.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Forms Data Format is defined in the PDF specification (since PDF 1.2).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The Forms Data Format can be used when submitting form data to a server, receiving the response, and incorporating it into the interactive form.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] It can also be used to export form data to stand-alone files that can be imported back into the corresponding PDF interactive form.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] FDF was originally defined in 1996 as part of ISO 32000-2:2017.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] (external XML Forms Data Format Specification, Version 2.0; supported since PDF 1.5; it replaced the "XML" form submission format defined in PDF 1.4) the XML version of Forms Data Format, but the XFDF implements only a subset of FDF containing forms and annotations.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Some entries in the FDF dictionary do not have XFDF equivalents – such as the Status, Encoding, JavaScript, Page's keys, EmbeddedFDFs, Differences, and Target.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In addition, XFDF does not allow the spawning, or addition, of new pages based on the given data; as can be done when using an FDF file.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The XFDF specification is referenced (but not included) in PDF 1.5 specification (and in later versions).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The PDF 1.4 specification allowed form submissions in XML format, but this was replaced by submissions in XFDF format in the PDF 1.5 specification.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] XFDF can be used in the same way as FDF; e.g., form data is submitted to a server, modifications are made, then sent back and the new form data is imported in an interactive form.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] This standard is a normative reference of ISO 32000-2.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The entire document can be submitted rather than individual fields and values, as was defined in PDF 1.4.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] AcroForms can keep form field values in external stand-alone files containing key-value pairs.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The external files may use Forms Data Format (FDF) and XML Forms Data Format (XFDF) files.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The usage rights (UR) signatures define rights for import form data files in FDF, XFDF, and text (CSV/TSV) formats, and export form data files in FDF and XFDF formats.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In PDF 1.5, Adobe Systems introduced a proprietary format for forms; Adobe XML Forms Architecture (XFA).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Adobe XFA Forms are not compatible with ISO 32000's AcroForms feature, and most PDF processors do not handle XFA content.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The XFA specification is referenced from ISO 32000-1/PDF 1.7 as an external proprietary specification and was entirely deprecated from PDF with ISO 32000-2 (PDF 2.0).
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Anyone may create applications that can read and write PDF files without having to pay royalties to Adobe Systems.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Adobe holds patents to PDF, but licenses them for royalty-free use in developing software complying with its PDF specification.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In November 2019, researchers from Ruhr University Bochum and Hackmanit GmbH published attacks on digitally signed PDFs.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] They showed how to change the visible content in a signed PDF without invalidating the signature in 21 of 22 desktop PDF viewers and 6 of 8 online validation services by abusing implementation flaws.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] At the same conference, they additionally showed how to exfiltrate the plaintext of encrypted content in PDFs.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In 2021, they showed new so-called *shadow attacks* on PDFs that abuse the flexibility of features provided in the specification.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] An overview of security issues in PDFs regarding denial of service, information disclosure, data manipulation, and arbitrary code execution attacks was presented by Jens Müller.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Some popular PDF readers have a history of security vulnerabilities that allows PDF files that have been infected with viruses, Trojans, and other malware to inflict damage.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Such PDF files can have hidden JavaScript code that might exploit vulnerabilities in a PDF reader, hidden objects executed when the file that hides them is opened, and, less commonly, a malicious PDF can launch malware.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF attachments carrying viruses were first discovered in 2001.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The virus, named *OUTLOOK.PDFWorm* or *Peachy*, uses Microsoft Outlook to send itself as an attached Adobe PDF file.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] It was activated with Adobe Acrobat, but not with Acrobat Reader.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Over the years, several vulnerabilities have been discovered in various versions of Adobe Reader, which prompted the company to issue security fixes.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Vulnerabilities have been discovered in other PDF readers as well.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] One aggravating factor is that a PDF reader can be configured to start automatically if a web page has an embedded PDF file, providing a vector for attack.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] If a malicious web page contains an infected PDF file that takes advantage of a vulnerability in the PDF reader, the system may be compromised even if the browser is secure.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Some of these vulnerabilities are a result of badly written PDF readers mishandling JavaScript embedded in the PDF file.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Disabling JavaScript execution in the PDF reader can help mitigate such future exploits, although it does not protect against exploits in other parts of the PDF viewing software.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Some security experts say that JavaScript is not essential for a PDF reader and that the security benefit that comes from disabling JavaScript outweighs any compatibility issues caused.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] One way of avoiding PDF file exploits is to have a local or web service convert files to another format before viewing.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] On March 30, 2010, security researcher Didier Stevens reported an Adobe Reader and Foxit Reader exploit that runs a malicious executable if the user allows it to launch when asked.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF streams can have nested filters, which allows one to craft a 5 kilobyte file that unpacks to 1 petabyte in RAM.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] This can be used to cause a denial of service with implementations that don't guard against this like it was the case with pypdf's CVE-2025-55197.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Many PDF viewers are provided free of charge from a variety of sources.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Programs to manipulate and edit PDF files are available, usually for purchase.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Additionally, most modern web browsers, including Chrome, Firefox, and Safari, include PDF viewing capabilities, replacing browser plugins that were previously created for such purposes.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] There are many software options for creating PDFs, including the PDF printing capabilities built into macOS, iOS, and most Linux distributions.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Much document processing software including LibreOffice, Microsoft Office 2007 (if updated to SP2) and later, WordPerfect 9, and Scribus can export documents in PDF.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Google's online office suite Google Docs allows uploading and saving to PDF.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Some web apps offer free PDF editing and annotation tools.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The Free Software Foundation was "developing a free, high-quality and fully functional set of libraries and programs that implement the PDF file format and associated technologies to the ISO 32000 standard", as one of its high priority projects.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In 2011, however, the GNU PDF project was removed from the list of "high priority projects" due to the maturation of the Poppler library, which has enjoyed wider use in applications such as Evince with the GNOME desktop environment.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] There are also commercial development libraries available as listed in List of PDF software.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The Apache PDFBox project of the Apache Software Foundation is an open source Java library, licensed under the Apache License, for working with PDF documents.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Raster image processors (RIPs) are used to convert PDF files into a raster format suitable for imaging onto paper and other media in printers, digital production presses and prepress in a process known as rasterization.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] RIPs capable of processing PDF directly include the Adobe PDF Print Engine from Adobe Systems and Jaws and the Harlequin RIP from Global Graphics.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In 1993, the Jaws raster image processor from Global Graphics became the first shipping prepress RIP that interpreted PDF natively without conversion to another format.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The company released an upgrade to its Harlequin RIP with the same capability in 1997.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Agfa-Gevaert introduced and shipped Apogee, the first prepress workflow system based on PDF, in 1997.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Many commercial offset printers have accepted the submission of press-ready PDF files as a print source, specifically the PDF/X-1a subset and variations of the same.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The submission of press-ready PDF files is a replacement for the problematic need for receiving collected native working files.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In 2006, PDF was widely accepted as the standard print job format at the Open Source Development Labs Printing Summit.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] It is supported as a print job format by the Common Unix Printing System and desktop application projects such as GNOME, KDE, Firefox, Thunderbird, LibreOffice and OpenOffice have switched to emit print jobs in PDF.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Some desktop printers also support direct PDF printing, which can interpret PDF data without external help.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] PDF was selected as the "native" metafile format for macOS (originally called Mac OS X), replacing the PICT format of the earlier classic Mac OS.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The imaging model of the Quartz graphics layer is based on the model common to Display PostScript and PDF, leading to the nickname *Display PDF*.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The Preview application can display PDF files, as can version 2.0 and later of the Safari web browser.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] System-level support for PDF allows macOS applications to create PDF documents automatically, provided they support the OS-standard printing architecture.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The files are then exported in PDF 1.3 format according to the file header.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] When taking a screenshot under Mac OS X versions 10.0 through 10.3, the image was also captured as a PDF; later versions save screen captures as a PNG file, though this behavior can be set back to PDF if desired.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Adobe Acrobat is one example of proprietary software that allows the user to annotate, highlight, and add notes to already created PDF files.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] One UNIX application available as free software (under the GNU General Public License) is PDFedit.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The freeware Foxit Reader, available for Microsoft Windows, macOS and Linux, allows annotating documents.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Tracker Software's PDF-XChange Viewer allows annotations and markups without restrictions in its freeware alternative.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Apple's macOS's integrated PDF viewer, Preview, does also enable annotations as does the open-source software Skim, with the latter supporting interaction with LaTeX, SyncTeX, and PDFSync and integration with BibDesk reference management software.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Freeware Qiqqa can create an annotation report that summarizes all the annotations and notes one has made across their library of PDFs.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The Text Verification Tool exports differences in documents as annotations and markups.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] There are also web annotation systems that support annotation in pdf and other document formats.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] In cases where PDFs are expected to have all of the functionality of paper documents, ink annotation is required.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Numerous tools and source code libraries support these tasks.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Several labeled datasets to test PDF conversion and information extraction tools exist and have been used for benchmark evaluations of the tool's performance.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] The Open XML Paper Specification is a competing format used both as a page description language and as the native print spooler format for Microsoft Windows since Windows Vista.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] Mixed Object: Document Content Architecture is a competing format.
[src:2016-winter-youth-olympics/pdf] MO:DCA-P is a part of Advanced Function Presentation.
